[Event "Baker Bridge - Squeeze Plays"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:A.A63.K5.AKQJ987 KQ963.Q985.9.T62 J8.K74.AJ8762.53 T7542.JT2.QT43.4"]
[Declarer "N"]
[Contract "7C"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
2C pass 3D pass 4NT pass 5D pass 5NT pass 6D pass 7C pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 1, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/squeeze_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{North is to play 7\C. East leads the \SK.

At first glance this doesn't appear to be a difficult hand. You expect to win the opening lead, pull trumps, then establish a \D winner by playing \DK, \DA, and ruffing a \D. As long as they split 3-2 you could reach dummy's \D winner with the \HK. 

So you take the \SA, pull three rounds of trumps and play \DK.

But when you lead to the \DA East discards a small \S. 

Time to rethink. You are in dummy now, and you can ruff a \D, return with the \HK and ruff another \D. The last \D would be good but you'd have no way to reach it. 

Think squeeze instead. Ruff a \D. This turns the \DJ into a Threat card against West's \DQ.

But, the \SJ is already a Threat card against East's \SQ. 

Play your \CJ and \C9, discarding the \D8 and the \H4 from dummy. 

East can afford to discard the \S9 and the \H5.

West can spare his two \Ss. 

[showcards N:SJ,HK,H7,DJ E:HJ,HT,H2,DQ S:HA,H6,H3,C8 W:SQ,HQ,H9,H8]

You are there. Play your \C8. 

East cannot throw the \SQ, so he gives up the \H8. Dummy's \SJ is of no further value so you dump it.

West cannot throw the \DQ, so he gives up the \H2.

And you take the last three tricks with the \H suit. There were only two defenders; one of them had to guard \Ss and the other had to guard \Ds. There was nobody left to guard \Hs.}
[Play "W"]SK

