2C 4S pass pass 5H pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/squeeze_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 6\H. South leads the \SA.

If \Ds and \Cs split nicely this would be an easy slam. But with that wild \S bid by South you can't expect decent splits.

So you ruff the \S, pull trumps in three rounds, then play \C A K and get the bad news when South discards a \S. 

You now know that North guards the \Cs. And since South had 3 \Hs and a very long \S suit it is pretty likely that North guards the \Ds also. You will try to squeeze North in \Cs and \Ds, but first you must lose a trick to rectify the count.

So you play a low \D from each hand. 

It doesn't matter which defender takes the \D, since either one is going to do the same thing. Assume South wins the \D10.

He will then play the \SK, which you must ruff in your hand. 

Now play a small \D to dummy's \DK. 

[showcards N:HJ,D7,C8,C6 E:DQ,DJ,CJ,CT S:DA,D8,CQ,C4 W:SJ,S8,S6,S5]

You are in dummy, ready for the squeeze.

Play dummy's \HJ.

North gets to choose his own fate - discarding a protector in one of the two suits. Of course, whichever suit he discards you will throw the opposite one.

Yet another slam, courtesy of the Squeeze Play!}
[Play "W"]SA

